	<p>The image of sport as a "field of battle" was created after the war, mostly for ideological and propagandistic purposes. The most celebrated example of the postwar transformation of history is the legend about the football "match of death" between the Kyiv team "Dynamo" and the Luftwaffe team in occupied Kyiv in August 1942.</p>
	<p>According to stories spread after the war, the occupiers gathered the Dynamo team and forced them to play against the German flyers, and ordered that under no circumstance should they win the match. For defying this order, the Germans promised death by shooting. Despite the threat, however, the Soviet players still won the game, and were immediately shot in Babyi Iar. For many this myth was a true story from World War II.</p>
	<p>As researchers know today, the legend about the "match of death" is based on real events—but only partly. On August 9 a team of workers from the bread factory "Start," a team composed primarily of players from Dynamo, really did enter the stadium "Zenith" and really did play the German amateur team "Flakelf." The Kyiv players also won—5 to 3. But it is hard to consider this particular match as anything special. The former Dynamo team members played several times against the Germans in occupied Kyiv--and won the majority of matches with no negative consequences. Four players from Dynamo were, in fact, shot, but for other reasons, although scholars have not quite yet clarified this matter.</p>
	
	
